            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>Memes spread because they use instantly recognizable formats, require zero effort to consume, are emotionally resonant (usually funny or relatable), and are easy to share. The remix culture — where users adapt the format to their own context — accelerates distribution exponentially.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
              <span class="faq-q-text">Should brands use memes in their social media strategy?</span>
              <span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>Memes can generate significant organic reach and build cultural relevance, but they carry real risks. Brands with younger audiences, casual brand tones, and fast internal approval processes are best positioned to use them. Brands with formal brand voices or risk-sensitive industries should be cautious.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
              <span class="faq-q-text">What makes a meme go viral?</span>
              <span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>Viral memes combine a recognizable format, a universal truth or shared frustration, and perfect cultural timing. Speed is critical — meme formats peak and decline in days. Brands that react within hours of a trend emerging capture the reach window; brands that react in days miss it entirely.</p></div></div>
          </div>
